 wp-image-310783" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Bloemfontein-scores.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="927" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Bloemfontein-scores.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Bloemfontein-scores-276x400.jpg 276w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Bloemfontein-scores-768x1113.jpg 768w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Bloemfontein-scores-297x430.jpg 297w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> Telkom and Vodacom were neck-and-neck in East London, posting similar average download speeds and achieving the same network quality score. Telkom was fractionally faster, with a download speed of 20.4Mbps compared to Vodacom’s 20.3Mbps. Cell C came close by virtue of its faster upload speed (10.9Mbps) and latency, but had slower average download speeds (16.6Mbps). MTN had an average download speed of 22.6Mbps. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-311507" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/East-London-scores.jpg" alt="Mobile network quality tests 2019 Q2 East London scores" width="640" height="782" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/East-London-scores.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/East-London-scores-328x400.jpg 328w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/East-London-scores-768x938.jpg 768w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/East-London-scores-352x430.jpg 352w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> The results weren’t as close in Port Elizabeth, with clear margins between the average download speeds: MTN was 25.3Mbps, Vodacom was 22.3Mbps, and Telkom was 20.5Mbps. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-317663" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Port-Elizabeth.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="966" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Port-Elizabeth.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Port-Elizabeth-265x400.jpg 265w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Port-Elizabeth-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Port-Elizabeth-285x430.jpg 285w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> MTN saw average download speeds of 29.1Mbps in Uitenhage. Telkom posted a solid average download speed of 26.7Mbps, but was far behind MTN in terms of upload speeds and latency. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-317811" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Uitenhage.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="900" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Uitenhage.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Uitenhage-284x400.jpg 284w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Uitenhage-768x1080.jpg 768w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Uitenhage-306x430.jpg 306w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /> Telkom took second place from Vodacom in the Eastern Cape, with slightly faster average download speeds — 21.3Mbps vs. 19.9Mbps. However, it should be noted that Telkom’s network footprint is much smaller than Vodacom’s, and it relies on a roaming agreement with Vodacom in the areas where it doesn’t have coverage. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-317813" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Eastern-Cape.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="708" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Eastern-Cape.jpg 800w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Eastern-Cape-3